Sentencas: Exsolution of active nanoparticles in oxide materials is an effective and feasible way to promote the catalytic activities of electrodes for solid oxide cells (SOCs).
Titulo: Promotion of Ca3Co4O9+δ oxygen electrode by in-situ exsolution of nanoparticles for solid oxide cells

Sentencas: In this study, Ca-site deficient CaxCo4O9+delta (CCO-x, x = 1.5, 2, 2.5) materials are facilely prepared and studied as oxygen electrodes of SOCs.
Titulo: Promotion of Ca3Co4O9+δ oxygen electrode by in-situ exsolution of nanoparticles for solid oxide cells

Sentencas: Co3O4 nanoparticles are in-situ exsolved and well embedded on the Ca3Co4O9+delta (CCO-3.0) surface by high-temperature annealing at 850 degrees C in ambient air.
Titulo: Promotion of Ca3Co4O9+δ oxygen electrode by in-situ exsolution of nanoparticles for solid oxide cells

Sentencas: Results proves an effectively promotion of the ORR and OER kinetics with Ca deficiency.
Titulo: Promotion of Ca3Co4O9+δ oxygen electrode by in-situ exsolution of nanoparticles for solid oxide cells

Sentencas: The polarization resistance of CCO-1.5 oxygen electrode reduces by 60% as compared with that of the CCO-3.0 electrode at 800 degrees C, from 0.23 to 0.09 omega cm2.
Titulo: Promotion of Ca3Co4O9+δ oxygen electrode by in-situ exsolution of nanoparticles for solid oxide cells

Sentencas: Both the peak power density and the electrolysis current density of the anode-supported SOC with CCO-1.5 oxygen electrode are more than 2 times that of the CCO-3.0 cell.
Titulo: Promotion of Ca3Co4O9+δ oxygen electrode by in-situ exsolution of nanoparticles for solid oxide cells

Sentencas: The improved electrochemical kinetics is attributed to the exsolved Co3O4 nanoparticles with high redox reactivity and the enhanced oxygen vacancy concentration.
Titulo: Promotion of Ca3Co4O9+δ oxygen electrode by in-situ exsolution of nanoparticles for solid oxide cells

Sentencas: Results make clear reliability of Ca-site deficient CaxCo4O9+delta as a promisingly oxygen electrodes for SOCs.
Titulo: Promotion of Ca3Co4O9+δ oxygen electrode by in-situ exsolution of nanoparticles for solid oxide cells
